    <!--Easy Blind Tab for Potential Project-->
    <div id="EasyBlind">
      <div class="row">
        <div class="col l12">
          <div class="card blue-grey hoverable" id="easyblindcard">
            <span class="card-title"><b>Easy Blind - Pending</b></span>
            <h5 class="dark grey-text" >Introduction</h5>
            <p class="flow-text">Easy Blind is an Arduino-based device that will utilize a photoresistor to detect the amount of light outside, and adjust the angle of your blinds accordingly. A bipolar stepper motor, controlled by an H-Bridge Integrated Circuit will be used to control the blinds in order to maximize precision.</p>
            <div class="divider"></div>
            <span class="black-text flow-text"><b>Key Learnings:</b></span>
            <ul class="collection">
              <li class="collection-item flow-text">Understanding control theory and applying the feedback loop in adjusting the blinds</li>
              <li class="collection-item flow-text">Learning how to work with and troubleshoot bipolar stepper motors</li>
              <li class="collection-item flow-text">Using Solidworks to design a piece that will attach the device to the blinds and 3-D printing it</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
    </div>

    <!--Fuel Cell Car-->
    <div id="FuelCellCar">
      <div class="row">
      <!--description of project-->
        <div class="col l12">
          <div class="card blue-grey hoverable" id="fuelcellcard">
            <div class="col l6">
              <div class="card-content white-text">
                <span class="card-title"><b>Project Description</b></span>
                <p class="flow-text">This project consists of a line following car powered by Hydrogen PEM Fuel Cells. The car utilized light and colour sensors to navigate a course, and a custom written algorithm written in C++ to handle forks in the path and dead-ends to reach the desired destination. A TI MSP430 microcontroller was used to control the two brushed DC motors.</p>
                <div class="section">
                  <div class="divider"></div>
                </div>
                <p class="flow-text" id="safenighttext2">The most important lesson I learned from this project is that when developing a product, factors besides the hardware and software development must be considered, like the economic, business, and environmental factors.  In order to ensure that the car would have the longest run time possible, the fuel cells had to be frequently hydrated. The temperature, humidity were some factors that had to be considered for storage as well. Consequently, this project inspired me to contribute to the eventual goal of vehicles on the road being powered by alternative means of energy</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="col l6">
              <div class="card-panel hoverable" id="safenightkeylearnings">
                <span class="black-text flow-text"><b>Key Learnings:</b></span>
                <ul class="collection">
                  <li class="collection-item flow-text">Learned how to develop a line following algorithm in C++ that could forks and dead-ends</li>
                  <li class="collection-item flow-text">Utilized our knowledge of the electrochemical reaction to design our car with double the hydrogen capacity to match the reactant proportions to increase the output voltage.</li>
                  <li class="collection-item flow-text">Implemented a calibration function to adjust the sensor according to lighting conditions</li>
                  <li class="collection-item flow-text">Equipped the car with sensor debouncing to reduce noise from the colour and light sensors.</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        
        
      </div>

